Here is a Java solution that checks if a given integer `n` is a power of three without using loops or recursion:

```java
public class PowerOfThree {
    public static boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        // The maximum power of 3 value that can be represented as an int
        int maxPowerOfThree = (int) Math.pow(3, (int) (Math.log(Integer.MAX_VALUE) / Math.log(3)));

        // Check if n is a power of three by checking if it divides the maxPowerOfThree
        return n > 0 && maxPowerOfThree % n == 0;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Test cases
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(27)); // Output: true
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(0));  // Output: false
        System.out.println(isPowerOfThree(-1)); // Output: false
    }
}
```

This solution works by first calculating the maximum integer that is a power of three (`maxPowerOfThree`). This value is calculated using the formula `3^(log_3(MAX_VALUE))`, where `MAX_VALUE` is the maximum value an integer can hold. Then, it checks if `n` is a divisor of `maxPowerOfThree`. If `n` is a power of three, it will divide `maxPowerOfThree` without a remainder. If `n` is not a power of three, it will not divide `maxPowerOfThree` evenly. This approach avoids the need for loops or recursion and is efficient for the given constraints.

